  "prompt": "Is money laundering considered a violation of the law?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is universally recognized as a serious criminal offense under both national and international law. Here\u2019s a detailed breakdown:\n\n### **Legal Status**:\n- **Global Criminalization**: Nearly all countries have laws criminalizing money laundering. It is prohibited because it enables criminal activities (e.g., drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption) by disguising the illicit origins of funds.\n- **Key Laws**:\n  - **United States**: The Bank Secrecy Act (1970), Money Laundering Control Act (1986), and the USA PATRIOT Act (2001).\n  - **European Union**: Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD) harmonize regulations across member states.\n  - **International Standards**: The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global guidelines, endorsed by over 200 jurisdictions.\n\n### **Consequences**:\n- **Penalties**: Convictions may result in severe fines, imprisonment (often decades-long sentences), asset forfeiture, and reputational damage.\n- **Broader Liability**: Even attempting, aiding, or conspiring to launder money is prosecutable.\n\n### **Purpose of Laws**:\n- **Disrupt Crime**: By targeting the financial infrastructure of criminal enterprises, these laws aim to deter illegal activities and protect economic systems.\n\n### **Enforcement**:\n- Agencies like the FBI, INTERPOL, and national financial intelligence units (e.g., FinCEN in the U.S.) collaborate to investigate and prosecute cases.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is unequivocally illegal worldwide, with robust legal frameworks and severe penalties to combat its role in sustaining criminal networks.",
